# Firestore Error Handling

When using Firestore `onSnapshot` (or similar listeners), **never throw in the error callback**. Throwing prevents `setLoading(false)` and leaves the UI stuck in a loading state.

## ❌ Wrong

```ts
onSnapshot(q, (snapshot) => {
  setData(/* ... */);
  setLoading(false);
}, (err) => {
  handleFirestoreError(err, op, path); // throws — setLoading(false) never runs
});
```

## ✅ Correct

```ts
onSnapshot(q, (snapshot) => {
  setData(/* ... */);
  setLoading(false);
  setError(null);
}, (err) => {
  handleFirestoreError(err, op, path, { throw: false });
  setLoading(false);
  setError(getFriendlyMessage(err));
});
```

## Additional Safeguards

- **Loading timeout**: Add a timeout (e.g. 15s) so loading always resolves if Firestore never responds.
- **Error UI**: Show user-facing error message and a "Try again" button.
- **Logging only**: Use `{ throw: false }` when you want to log but not propagate.
